    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3723025809" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3723025809" />
    <a title="Matthew Johnson" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16280913-matthew-johnson"><img alt="Matthew Johnson" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1609449920p2/16280913.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3723025809?book_show_action=true">Dec 28, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Matthew Johnson" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Matthew Johnson" href="/user/show/16280913-matthew-johnson">Matthew Johnson</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3723025809" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5816066077944332052">I hate to be controversial, we all love Steven and we all admire him as an inspirational figure and symbol of triumphing over adversity, and of likability and pure intelligence. However......I have a background in science and I have tried to read a brief history of time, a briefer history of time, this book, and brief answers to the big questions; and after much deliberation, I have concluded that it just doesn&apos;t make much sense. That is to say, I don&apos;t believe that even educated laypeople can r</span>
  <span id="freeText5816066077944332052" style="display:none">I hate to be controversial, we all love Steven and we all admire him as an inspirational figure and symbol of triumphing over adversity, and of likability and pure intelligence. However......I have a background in science and I have tried to read a brief history of time, a briefer history of time, this book, and brief answers to the big questions; and after much deliberation, I have concluded that it just doesn't make much sense. That is to say, I don't believe that even educated laypeople can really understand these theories in any meaningful or useful way, despite his efforts and skill. I lose the train of logic by halfway in each book and it just turns to gibberish. I can't help but suspect that many people are merely understanding some superficial aspects of his theories and are just content with that; rate it 5 stars and gush about how interesting and important a book it is. <br /><br />It reminds me a bit of everyone that had business relations with Enron in the year 2000. No one was confident enough to say that their financial deals didn't make sense since Enron was "America's Most Innovative Company" for the last six consecutive years and the executives were the best of the best. So they convinced themselves that they just didn't understand Enrons genius and happily bought in. But in reality, it was all just bullshit. </span>
  <a data-text-id="5816066077944332052" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


